<p><a name="Description_of_the_Scheimpflug_principle" id="Description_of_the_Scheimpflug_principle"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Scheimpflug_principle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Description of the Scheimpflug principle">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Description of the Scheimpflug principle</span></h2>
<table align="right" cellpadding="0">
<tr>
<td>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:DOF-ShallowDepthofField.jpg" class="image" title="Figure 1. With a normal camera, when the subject is not parallel to the image plane, only a small region is in focus."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/DOF-ShallowDepthofField.jpg/300px-DOF-ShallowDepthofField.jpg" width="300" height="216" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:DOF-ShallowDepthofField.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Figure 1. With a normal camera, when the subject is not parallel to the image plane, only a small region is in focus.</div>
</div>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Scheimpflug.gif" class="image" title="Figure 2. The angles of the Scheimpflug principle, using the example of a photographic lens."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4f/Scheimpflug.gif" width="300" height="208" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Scheimpflug.gif" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
